Microservices with MongoDB - 3 tier project

New Project: Scalable 3-Tier Chat Application on Kubernetes

I recently designed and deployed a full-stack, 3-tier Chat Application orchestrated entirely within a Kubernetes environment. This project
allowed me to dive deep into container orchestration, cloud networking, and microservices management.

System Architecture

1. Frontend Tier: React/Node.js web UI exposed safely via a Kubernetes Ingress Controller for seamless external traffic routing.
2. Backend Tier: Node.js API handling business logic and application state, managed as an independent scalable deployment.
3. Database Tier: MongoDB instance deployed cluster-internal to manage chat data and secure user records.

Key Troubleshooting & Engineering Wins
No deployment goes perfectly, and the real learning happened while debugging the infrastructure:

1. Internal DNS & Service Discovery Resolution: Resolved a backend-to-database connection failure. Discovered the backend configuration was
targeting a generic mongodb:27017 address instead of the correct cluster-internal CoreDNS Service hostname mapping back to the database pod
labels.
2. Securing Local Environments: Overcame OS-level port binding constraints (permission denied on privileged port 80) during local testing
cycles by leveraging secure high-port mapping mechanisms over kubectl port-forward.
3. Production-Ready Ingress Routing: Successfully transitioned the architecture from basic port-forwarding to a robust production setup 
using Ingress routing rules, enabling cleaner traffic distribution and path-based routing.

